04547nam a22007095i 9781503633018DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021052379  a97815036330187 a10.1515/97815036330182doi  a(DE-B1597)641551  a(OCoLC)1350570512  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPR447b.E45 2022 4aPR447b.E45 2022 7aLIT0041802bisacsh04a820.9/36223/eng/202204101 aEllermann, Greg, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThought’s Wilderness :bRomanticism and the Apprehension of Nature /cGreg Ellermann. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Romanticism and Real Abstraction -- t2 Kant’s Remaining Time -- t3 Hegel in and Out of the Woods -- t4 Wollstonecraft in Ruins -- t5 Accidental Revelation in Words worth -- t6 Shelley’s Ethereal Poetics -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile much recent ecocriticism has questioned the value of nature as a concept, Thought's Wilderness insists that it is analytically and politically indispensable, and that romanticism shows us why. Without a concept of nature, Greg Ellermann argues, our thinking is limited to the world that capitalism has made. Defamiliarizing the tradition of romantic nature writing, Ellermann contends that the romantics tried to circumvent the domination of nature that is essential to modern capitalism. As he shows, poets and philosophers in the period such as Immanuel Kant, G. W. F. Hegel, Mary Wollstonecraft, William Wordsworth, and Percy Shelley were highly attuned to nature's ephemeral, ungraspable forms: clouds of vapor, a trace of ruin, deep silence, and the "world-surrounding ether." Further, he explains how nature's vanishing—its vulnerability and its flight from apprehension—became a philosophical and political problem. In response to a nascent industrial capitalism, romantic writers developed a poetics of wilderness—a poetics that is attentive to fleeting presence and that seeks to let things be. Trying to imagine what ultimately eludes capture, the romantics recognized the complicity between conceptual and economic domination, and they saw how thought itself could become a technology for control. This insight, Ellermann proposes, motivates romantic efforts to think past capitalist instrumentality and its devastation of the world. Ultimately, this new work undertakes a fundamental rethinking of the aesthetics and politics of nature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNature in literature. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 0aPhilosophy, Germany18th century. 0aPhilosophy, Germany19th century. 0aRomanticismzEngland. 0aRomanticismzGermany. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh  aaesthetics.  acapitalism.  aconsciousness.  aecology.  anature.  aphilosophy.  apoetry.  aromanticism.  awilderness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363301840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503633018/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles